        </solutions>
      </section>
      <section xml:id="sec-more-logic-laws">
        <title>
          More Laws of Logic
        </title>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-demorgans-laws">
          <title>De Morgan's Laws</title>
          <p>
            Consider the following truth table:
            <tabular halign="center" top="major" left="medium">
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>q</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand q</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mynot(p\myand q)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\notp</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\notq</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\notp\,\myor\,\notq</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  1
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  0
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </p>
          <p>
            From this table we can see that
            <me>\mynot(p\myand q)\Leftrightarrow\notp\,\myor\notq.</me>
            We can construct a similar table to show that
            <me>\mynot(p\myor q)\Leftrightarrow\notp\,\myand\notq.</me>
            These are called <term>De Morgan's Laws</term>.
            <idx><h>laws of logic</h><h>De Morgan's laws</h></idx>
            <idx>De Morgan's laws</idx>
            Constructing the tables using Boolean algebra notation yields similar statements.
          </p>
          <p>
            <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-demorgans-laws">
              <title>De Morgan's Laws</title>
              <p>
                <sidebyside width="30%" margins="15%">
                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <alert>Logic</alert>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>\mynot(p\myand q)\amp\Leftrightarrow\,\notp\,\myor\notq</mrow>
                          <mrow>\mynot(p\myor q)\amp\Leftrightarrow\,\notp\,\myand\notq.</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>

                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <alert>Boolean</alert>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>\mybnot{A\cdot B}\amp =\nota+\notb</mrow>
                          <mrow>\mybnot{A+B}\amp =\nota\cdot\notb</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </sidebyside>
              </p>
            </assemblage>
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-distributive-laws">
          <title>Distributive Laws</title>
          <p>
            In the same way, we can construct truth tables to prove the <term>distributive laws</term>, in both logic and Boolean algebra notation.
            <idx><h>laws of logic</h><h>distributive laws</h></idx>
            <idx>distributive laws</idx>
            Note carefully the forms of these laws.
            <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-distributive-laws">
              <title>Distributive Laws</title>
              <p>
                <sidebyside width="30%" margins="auto">
                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <alert>Logic</alert>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>p\myand(q\myor r)\amp\Leftrightarrow(p\myand q)\myor(p\myand r)</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\myor(q\myand r)\amp\Leftrightarrow(p\myor q)\myand(p\myor r)</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>

                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <alert>Boolean</alert>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>A(B+C)\amp =AB+AC</mrow>
                          <mrow>A+BC\amp =(A+B)(A+C)</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </sidebyside>
              </p>
            </assemblage>
            The first of the distributive laws in Boolean notation looks like the usual one from arithmetic with real numbers.  The second one, however, looks decidedly <em>unlike</em> any rules from arithmetic.  You must not let the familiar rules of arithmetic distract you from the laws of logic.
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-absorption-laws">
          <title>Absorption Laws</title>
          <p>
            The <term>absorption laws</term> can be verified using truth tables, or by use of the laws of logic already stated.
            <idx><h>laws of logic</h><h>absorption laws</h></idx>
            <idx>absorption laws</idx>
            <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-absorption-laws">
              <title>Absorption Laws</title>
              <p>
                <sidebyside width="30%" margins="auto">
                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <alert>Logic</alert>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>p\myand(p\myor q)\amp\Leftrightarrow p</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\myand(\notp\,\myor\,q)\amp\Leftrightarrow\,p\myand q</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\myor(p\myand q)\amp\Leftrightarrow\,p</mrow>
                          <mrow>p\myor(\notp\,\myand\,q)\amp\Leftrightarrow\,p\myor q</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>

                  <tabular>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                      <cell>
                        <alert>Boolean</alert>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>
                        <md>
                          <mrow>A(A+B)\amp=A</mrow>
                          <mrow>A(\nota+B)\amp=AB</mrow>
                          <mrow>A+AB\amp=A</mrow>
                          <mrow>A+\nota{}B\amp=A+B</mrow>
                        </md>
                      </cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </sidebyside>
              </p>
            </assemblage>
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-summary-logic-laws">
          <title>Summary So Far</title>
          <p>
            Here are all the laws of logic discussed so far:
            <idx><h>laws of logic</h><h>summary</h></idx>
            <tabular halign="center" top="major" left="medium">
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Law
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  Logic
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  Boolean Algebra
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Identity
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myand{} 1 \myleq{} p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A \cdot 1 = A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myor{}1 \myleq{}  1</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+1 = 1</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myand{} 0 \myleq{}  0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A \cdot 0 = 0</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myor{}0 \myleq{}  p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+0 = A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Idempotent
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myand{} p \myleq{}  p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>AA = A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myor{} p \myleq{}  p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+A = A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Complement
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mylnot{(\mylnot{p})}  \myleq{} p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mybnot{\nota{}} = A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myand{} \mylnot{p}  \myleq{}  0</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A\nota{} = 0</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myor{}\mylnot{p}  \myleq{}  1</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+ \nota{} = 1</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Commutative
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myand{} q \myleq{}  q \myand{} p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>AB = BA</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p \myor{}q \myleq{}   q \myor{} p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+ B = B + A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Associative
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m> (p \myand{} q) \myand{} r \myleq{}  p \myand{} (q \myand{} r) </m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>(AB)C = A(BC) </m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m> (p \myor{} q) \myor{} r \myleq{}  p \myor{} (q \myor{} r) </m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>(A+B)+C = A+(B+C) </m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  De Morgan's
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mylnot{(p \myand{} q)} \myleq{} \notp{} \myor{} \notq{}</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mybnot{AB} = \nota{} + \notb{}</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mylnot{(p \myor{} q)} \myleq{} \notp{} \myand{} \notq{}</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>\mybnot{A+B} = \nota{} ~ \notb{}</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Distributive
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand{}(q\myor{}r) \myleq{} (p\myand{}q)\myor{}(p\myand{}r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A(B+C) = AB + AC</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor{}(q\myand{}r) \myleq{} (p\myor{}q)\myand{}(p\myor{}r)</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+BC = (A+B)(A+C)</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                  Absorption
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand{}(p\myor{}q) \myleq{} p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A(A+B) = A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myand{}(\notp{}\myor{}q) \myleq{}  p\myand{}q</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A(\nota{} + B) = AB</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor{}(p\myand{}q) \myleq{}  p</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A + AB = A</m>
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell left="medium" right="medium">
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>p\myor{}(\notp{}\myand{}q) \myleq{}  p\myor{}q</m>
                </cell>
                <cell right="medium">
                  <m>A+ \nota{}B = A+ B </m>
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            The next sub-section contains examples of the usage of these laws.
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-simplifying-logical-expr2">
          <title>Simplifying Logical Expressions</title>
          <idx><h>logical equivalence</h><h>using laws of logic</h></idx>
          <idx><h>logical proposition</h><h>simplifying with laws of logic</h></idx>
          <p>
            The clarity of your simplification or of your proof is greatly improved if you use only one law in each line of your work, and also state the law you have used.  To help you build good habits, this is <alert>required</alert> in your coursework.  It is not merely a suggestion.
          </p>
          <example xml:id="exmpl-simpl-dist1">
            <statement>
              Simplify <m>(p\myand{}q)\myor(p\myand\notq)</m>.
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <tabular halign="center">
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>(p\myand{}q) \myor{}(p\myand{}\notq{})</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>p\myand{}(q\myor{}\notq{}) </m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    distributive
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>p\myand{}1 </m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    complement
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>p  </m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    identity
                  </cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </answer>
          </example>
          <example xml:id="exmpl-simpl-dist2">
            <statement>
              Simplify <m>AB(\nota{} + \notb{} )</m>.
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <tabular halign="center">
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>AB(\nota{} +\notb{})</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>AB\nota{}  + AB\notb{}   </m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    distributive
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>A\nota{} B + AB\notb{}  </m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    commutative
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>0 \cdot B      + A\cdot 0  </m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    complement
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>0        +       0    </m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    identity
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>
                    <m>       0            </m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell halign="left">
                    definition of or
                  </cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </answer>
          </example>
          <p>
            Note that for many of these exercises, there is more than one way to answer.  Another equally valivd simplification of the statement in the previous example looks like the following:
            <tabular halign="center">
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>AB(\nota{} +\notb{})</m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m>AB   \mybnot{AB} </m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  De Morgan's
                </cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>
                  <m> 0 </m>
                </cell>
                <cell halign="left">
                  complement
                </cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            This is a much shorter answer, but does require a flash of insight at the <m>(\nota + \notb)</m> pattern.
          </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection xml:id="ssec-proofs">
          <title>
            Proofs
          </title>
          <idx><h>proofs</h><h>using laws of logic</h></idx>
          <idx><h>laws of logic</h><h>proofs</h></idx>
          <idx><h>proposition</h><h>proofs</h></idx>
          <p>
            When tasked to prove that two logic statements are equivalent, look to see if one of the statements is simpler than the other.  Try to simplify the more complicated statement until it is identical to the simpler statement.  Sometimes, you will have to simplify both statements into identical forms.
          </p>
          <example xml:id="exmpl-proof1">
            <statement>
              Show that <m>\mybnot{A+\mybnot{A}\,\mybnot{B}}=\mybnot{A}B</m>.
            </statement>
            <answer>
              Let's examine the left-had side and simplify it.
              <tabular>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>\mybnot{A+\mybnot{A}\,\mybnot{B}}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>\mybnot{A}B</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>\mybnot{A+\mybnot{B}}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>\mybnot{A}B</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    absorption
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>\mybnot{A}\,\mybnot{\mybnot{B}}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>\mybnot{A}B</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    De Morgan's
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>\mybnot{A}B</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>\mybnot{A}B</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    complement
                  </cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
              <p>
                The left-hand side has been shown to be equivalent to the origintal right-hand side.  This completes the proof.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </example>
          <example xml:id="exmpl-proof2">
            <statement>
              Show that <m>(A+\mybnot{C})(\mybnot{C}+AB)=AB+\mybnot{C}</m>.
            </statement>
            <answer>
              The left side is more complicated, so let's examine it to see what simplification is possible.
              <tabular>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>(A+\mybnot{C})(\mybnot{C}+AB)</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>AB+\mybnot{C}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>(\mybnot{C}+A)(\mybnot{C}+AB)</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>AB+\mybnot{C}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    commutative
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>\mybnot{C}+A(AB)</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>AB=\mybnot{C}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    distributive
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>\mybnot{C}+(AA)B</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>AB=\mybnot{C}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    associative
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>\mybnot{C}+AB</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>AB+\mybnot{C}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    idempotent
                  </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right">
                    <m>AB+\mybnot{C}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>=</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    <m>AB+\mybnot{C}</m>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                    commutative
                  </cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
              QED.  (QED is short for the Latin phrase <em>quod erat demonstrandum</em>, which means <em>it has been demonstrated</em>.)
            </answer>
          </example>
        </subsection>
        <exercises xml:id="exers-sec-more-logic-laws">
          <exercisegroup>
            <introduction>
              Let <m>p</m> be the statement <em>Rich is seven feet tall</em> and <m>q</m> be <em>Susan has brown hair.</em>  Translate the following English sentences into logical notation.  Then, use one of the laws of logic to write an equivalent logical expression.  Finally, translate your new expression back into an English sentence.
            </introduction>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ </m>Rich is seven feet tall or he is seven feet tall.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <m>p \myor{} p  \myleq{}  p</m>.  Rich is seven feet tall.
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ </m>Susan has brown hair and she has brown hair.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <m>q  \myand{}  q  \myleq{}  q</m>.  Susan has brown hair.
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ </m>Either Rich is not seven feet tall or Susan does not have brown hair.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <m>\notp{} \myor{} \notq{}  \myleq{}  \mylnot{(p \myand{} q)}</m>.  It is not the case that Rich is seven feet tall and Susan has brown hair.
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ </m>It is not true that Rich is seven feet tall and Susan has brown
              </statement> hair.
              <solution>
                <m>\mylnot{(p \myand{} q)} \myleq{} \notp{} \myor{}  \notq{}</m>.  Rich is not seven feet tall or Susan does not have brown hair.
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ </m>It is not true that Rich is seven feet tall or Susan has brown hair.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <m>\mylnot{(p \myor{} q)}  \myleq{}  \notp{} \myand{}  \notq{}</m>.  Rich is not seven feet tall and Susan does not have brown hair.
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ </m>Rich is not seven feet tall and Susan does not have brown hair.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <m>\notp{} \myand{}  \notq{}    \myleq{}  \mylnot{(p \myor{} q)}</m>.  It is not the case that Rich is seven feet tall or Susan has brown hair.
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ </m>Rich is seven feet tall and Susan has brown hair.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <m>p \myand{} q  \myleq{}  q \myand{} p</m>.  Susan has brown hair and Rich is seven feet tall.
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ </m>Susan has brown hair or Rich is seven feet tall.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <m>q \myor{} p  \myleq{}  p \myor{} q</m>.  Rich is seven feet tall or Susan has brown hair.
              </solution>
            </exercise>
          </exercisegroup>
          <exercisegroup>
            <introduction>
              Name the law of logic used in the following.  note that the variables have changed, but that the law is still valid.
            </introduction>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ g\mylnot{(q \myor{} r)} \myleq \notq{} \myand{} \notr{}</m>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                De Morgan's
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ \notb{} (B + \nota{}) = \notb{}~\nota{} </m>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                absorption
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                <m>\ (p \myand{} q) \myor{} (p \myand \notq{}) \myleq{} p \myand{} (q \myor{}\notq{})</m>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                distributive
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
